## 5. Domain Models

Use `sealed record` for internal domain models. Keep proto-generated types at the gRPC boundary only.

```csharp
// Models/YourDomainRecord.cs  — internal domain model, not proto-generated
public sealed record YourDomainRecord
{
    public required string Id { get; init; }
    public required string Reference { get; init; }
    public required string Status { get; init; }
    public required DateTimeOffset CreatedAt { get; init; }
}
```

### Explicit mapping — proto ↔ domain

```csharp
// Models/YourDomainMappings.cs
internal static class YourDomainMappings
{
    internal static YourDomainRecord ToDomain(this YourDomainEntity entity) =>
        new()
        {
            Id = entity.Id,
            Reference = entity.Reference,
            Status = entity.Status,
            CreatedAt = entity.CreatedAt
        };

    internal static RecordResponse ToResponse(this YourDomainRecord record) =>
        new()
        {
            Id = record.Id,
            Reference = record.Reference,
            Status = record.Status,
            CreatedAtUnix = record.CreatedAt.ToUnixTimeMilliseconds()
        };

    internal static YourDomainRecord ToDomain(this CreateRequest request) =>
        new()
        {
            Id = Guid.NewGuid().ToString(),
            Reference = request.Reference,
            Status = "Open",
            CreatedAt = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow
        };
}
```

### Domain exceptions

```csharp
public sealed class YourDomainNotFoundException : Exception
{
    public string RecordId { get; }
    public YourDomainNotFoundException(string id) : base($"Record '{id}' was not found.")
        => RecordId = id;
}

public sealed class YourDomainDuplicateException : Exception
{
    public string Reference { get; }
    public YourDomainDuplicateException(string reference) : base($"Reference '{reference}' already exists.")
        => Reference = reference;
}
```

