## 10. Adding a New Feature — Step-by-Step

```
1. Add message types to proto   →  Protos/{{ model.manifest.service_name }}.proto
2. Regenerate proto (automatic on build)
3. Define domain model          →  Models/YourDomainXxx.cs
4. Define domain exceptions     →  Exceptions/YourDomainXxxException.cs
5. Extend service interface     →  Services/I{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}.cs
6. Update entity + migration    →  Data/YourDomainEntity.cs + dotnet ef migrations add
7. Implement repository method  →  Data/YourDomainRepository.cs
8. Implement service method     →  Services/{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}Impl.cs (log + trace + metrics)
9. Add RPC override             →  ServiceImpl.cs (map status codes)
10. Write tests                 →  Tests/Services/ + Tests/Grpc/
11. Verify coverage             →  dotnet test --collect:"XPlat Code Coverage"
```

---

## 11. What NOT To Do

| Don't | Do instead |
|---|---|
| Put business logic in `ServiceImpl` | Move it to `{{ model.names.dot_net_class_name }}` service |
| Throw raw exceptions from `ServiceImpl` | Map to `RpcException` with correct `StatusCode` |
| Use proto-generated types inside domain logic | Define internal domain models, map at the boundary |
| Use AutoMapper | Write explicit mapping methods |
| Call Genesis providers from `ServiceImpl` | Go through the service |
| Use `.Result` or `.Wait()` | `await` all async calls |
| Log PII | Log IDs and operation names only |
| Add NuGet packages without approval | Raise a ticket per dependency governance |
| Modify `Program.cs` | Raise a Pervaxis platform ticket |
| Skip tests | 90% coverage is a CI gate |

